summary:
The most commonly observed initial valvular change due to acute rheumatic fever involves the mitral valve. Mitral regurgitation appears more frequently than other valves like the aorta during its onset phase. To summarize:

The earliest and most frequent valvular manifestation in acute rheumatic fever is mitral regurgitation involving the mitral valve. This occurs before or concurrently with potential lesions affecting other heart valves such as the aorta. \boxed{\text{Mitral Regurgitation}} Summary by Agent2: 

In cases of acute rheumatic fever, the earliest identifiable valvular issue typically affects the mitral valve through mitral regurgitation, which happens more often compared to other valves including the aortic one at disease onset.\boxed{\text{Mitral Regurgitation}}
